<head><date value="1861-08-05" authname="1861-08-05">Monday morning........Aug. 5, 1861.</date><lb />the war.</head> 
<argument> 
<head /> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="641" /> address to the <orgName n="Army" type="military">Army</orgName> from <persName n="Johnston,General,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00473" reg="nearbymention:Johnston,J.,E.,," authname="johnston,j.,e."><roleName n="General" full="yes">Generals</roleName> <surname full="yes">Johnston</surname></persName> and <persName n="Beauregard,General,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00474" reg="nearbymention:Beauregard,G.,T.,," authname="beauregard,g.,t."><roleName n="General" full="yes" /><surname full="yes">Beauregard</surname></persName>--list of the enemy's killed and wounded officers, &amp;c. </p> </argument> 
<div3 type="article" n="1" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head /> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="642" /> The following eloquent address of our <rs type="role2">Generals</rs> to the army under their command will <unclear>-e </unclear> the patriotic emotions of every Southern reader. </p> 
<div4 type="entry" n="1" org="uniform" sample="complete"> 
<head rend="smallcaps">Headquarters <orgName n="Army of the Potomac" type="army">Army of the Potomac</orgName>,</head> <opener> <dateline> <name type="place">Manassas,</name> <date value="1861-07-25" authname="1861-07-25">July 25th, 1861.</date> </dateline> </opener> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="643" /> <hi rend="italics"><unclear /> of the <placeName reg="United States" key="tgn,7012149" authname="tgn,7012149">Confederate States</placeName>:</hi> </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="644" /> <num value="1">One</num> week ago a countless host of men <unclear>or-</unclear> into an army, with all the appointers which modern art and practiced skill <unclear /> devise, invaded the soil of <placeName reg="Virginia, United States, North and Central America" key="tgn,7007919" authname="tgn,7007919">Virginia</placeName>.--<unclear /> people sounded their approach with triumphant displays of anticipated victory.--<unclear /> <rs type="role2">Generals</rs> came in almost royal state; <unclear> </unclear> great Ministers, <rs type="role2">Senators</rs> and women, <unclear /> to witness the immolation of our army, <unclear /> the subjugation of our people, and to celebrate the result with wild revelry. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="645" /> <unclear /> with the profoundest emotions of gratitude to an over ruling <name n="God" type="God">God</name>, whose hand is <unclear>man-</unclear> in protecting our homes and our <unclear>liber-</unclear> that we, your <rs type="role2">Generals</rs> commanding, are bled, in the name of our whole country, thank you for that patriotic courage, that <unclear /> gallantry, that devoted daring exhibitory you in the actions of the <num value="18" type="ordinal">18th</num> and <num value="21" type="ordinal">21st</num>, which the hosts of the enemy were scattered, and a signal and glorious victory <unclear>ob-</unclear> </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="646" /> The <num value="2">two</num> affairs of the <num value="18" type="ordinal">18th</num> and <num value="21" type="ordinal">21st</num> were but <unclear /> remained and continued effort of your patriotism against the constantly recurring <unclear>col-</unclear> of an enemy, fully treole your number and their efforts were crowned on the <unclear>-ning</unclear> of the <num value="21" type="ordinal">21st</num> with a victory so complete <unclear /> the invaders are driven disgracefully in the field, and made to fly in disorderly <unclear /> back to their entrenchments, a distance over <measure n="30miles" type="distance">thirty miles</measure>. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="647" /> They left upon the field nearly every piece of their a <unclear>-ery,</unclear> a large portion of their aims, <unclear>-ments,</unclear> baggage, stores, &amp;c., &amp;c., and <unclear> </unclear> every <num value="1">one</num> of their wounded and dead, <unclear /> together with the prisoners, to many <num value="1000">thousands</num>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="648" />And thus the <rs>Northern</rs> <unclear /> were driven from <placeName reg="Virginia, United States, North and Central America" key="tgn,7007919" authname="tgn,7007919">Virginia</placeName>. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="649" /> Soldiers we congratulate you on an event which ensures the liberty of our country.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="650" />We congratulate every man of you, whose <unclear>-ous</unclear> privilege it was to participate in this prompt of courage and of truth — to fight in the <rs n="Battle of Manassas" type="battle">battle of Manassas</rs>.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="651" />You have created an <unclear /> in the history of Liberty, and unborn nations will rise up and call you "blessed" </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="652" /> Continue this noble devotion, looking always to the protection of a just <name n="God" type="God">God</name>, and belongs time grows much older, we will be hailed <unclear /> <unclear>-verers</unclear> of a nation of <num value="10000000">ten millions</num> of people. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="653" /> <unclear /> our brothers who have fallen <unclear /> earned undying renown upon earth, and his bloodshed in our holy cause is a pretense and acceptable sacrifice to the <rs>Father</rs> of Truth and of Right. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="654" /> Their graves are beside the tomb of <persName n="Washington,,,,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00475" reg="mostcommon:Washington,L.,B.,P.,:1" authname="washington,l.,b.,p."><surname full="yes">Washington</surname></persName>, their spirits have joined with his in <unclear> </unclear> communion. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="655" /> We will hold fast to the soil in which the <unclear /> of <placeName reg="Washington, District of Columbia, United States" key="tgn,7013962" authname="tgn,7013962">Washington</placeName> is thus mingled with the just of our brothers.

<milestone unit="sentence" n="656" />We will transmit this land free to our children, or we will fall into the fresh graves of our brothers-in-<unclear />. We drop <num value="1">one</num> tear on their laurels and more forward to avenge them. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="657" /> Soldiers' we congratulate you on a glorious, triumphant, and complete victory, and we thank you for doing your <hi rend="italics">whole duty</hi> in the name of your country. </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="658" /> (Signed) <hi rend="smallcaps"><persName n="Johnston,,J.,E.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00476" reg="default:Johnston,J.,E.,," authname="johnston,j.,e."><foreName full="yes">J.</foreName> <foreName full="yes">E.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Johnston</surname></persName>,</hi> </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="659" /> General <orgName n="C. S. Army">C. S. A.</orgName> </p> 
<p>

<milestone unit="sentence" n="660" /> (Signed) <hi rend="smallcaps"><persName n="Beauregard,,G.,T.,," id="n-0001.0000.00000.00477" reg="default:Beauregard,G.,T.,," authname="beauregard,g.,t."><foreName full="yes">G.</foreName> <foreName full="yes">T.</foreName> <surname full="yes">Beauregard</surname></persName>,</hi> </p> 
<p>

